WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
The mammary artery has been used in coronary vascularization for years starting in the 50s as part of the Vineberg procedure in which the mammary artery was implanted directly to the myocardium.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:20.000
The technique of direct coronary anastomosis with the aid of magnifying loupes was perfected at the Cleveland Clinic by Favaloro and his associates.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:28.000
And in this paper by Loop and associates from the Cleveland Clinic published in the New England Journal of Medicine in 1986,

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:44.000
the superiority of a mammary artery compared to saphenous vein grafts was demonstrated both in terms of graft patency and clinical outcomes and established the mammary to LAD as the quintessential component of a CABG.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:50.000
In this video, we start by showing the harvesting of the right internal mammary artery.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.000
The left internal mammary artery has already been harvested.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
We utilize the non-touch technique with minimal manipulation of the conduit itself.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:10.000
We grab the periadventitial tissue and fat and use the forceps to push the conduit away from the surrounding tissues.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Branches are controlled with the use of electrocautery or application of hemoclips as demonstrated here.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:33.000
The field has to be bloodless.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:54.000
The use of a piece of gauze to apply traction is also a useful atraumatic technique in harvesting skeletonized mammaries or for that matter, pedicled mammaries.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:12.000
If you get into bleeding, take time to carefully identify the branch source, control it and apply a clip as demonstrated here.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:21.000
The electrocautery is usually set at 20 or 30 to minimize the risk of thermal injury to the conduit.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Our aim is to harvest a mammary that has minimal hematomas and looks white and suffers no spasm.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Here, one of the terminal branches of the right internal mammary artery is being clipped and cut.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Notice that a nice lengthy skeletonized mammary ends with supplying the right diaphragm.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Next, we move proximally to mobilize the mammary.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:03.000
We use the fingers of the left hand to retract on the mammary and push away the lungs.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:20.999
In addition, we ask for anesthesia&#x2019;s help to use low tidal volumes or hold ventilation as necessary to achieve our objective.